msgstr "Mail server (MX)|First found affected cipher|Status"

msgid "detail mail tls ciphers verdict bad"
msgstr ""
"At least one of your mail servers supports one or more *insufficiently* "
"secure ciphers."

msgid "detail mail tls ciphers verdict good"
msgstr "All your mail servers support secure ciphers only."

msgid "detail mail tls ciphers verdict phase-out"
msgstr ""
"At least one of your mail servers supports one or more ciphers that have a "
"*phase out* status, because they are known to be fragile and are at risk of "
"becoming *insufficiently* secure."

msgid "detail mail tls compression exp"
msgstr ""
"We check if your receiving mail servers (MX) support TLS compression. \n"
"\n"
"The use of compression can give an attacker information about the secret parts of encrypted communication. An attacker that can determine or control parts of the data sent can reconstruct the original data by performing a large number of requests. TLS compression is used so rarely that disabling it is generally not a problem. \n"
"\n"
"See ['IT Security Guidelines for Transport Layer Security (TLS) v2.1'](https://english.ncsc.nl/publications/publications/2021/january/19/it-security-guidelines-for-transport-layer-security-2.1) from NCSC-NL, guideline B7-1 and table 11 (in English).\n"
"\n"
"---\n"
"**Compression option**\n"
"\n"
"* Good: No compression\n"
"* Sufficient: Application-level compression\n"
"* Insufficient: TLS compression"

msgid "detail mail tls compression label"
msgstr "TLS compression"

msgid "detail mail tls compression tech table"
msgstr "Mail server (MX)|TLS compression"

msgid "detail mail tls compression verdict bad"
msgstr ""
"At least on of your mail servers supports TLS compression, which is *not* "
"secure."

msgid "detail mail tls compression verdict good"
msgstr "All your mail servers do not support TLS compression."

msgid "detail mail tls dane-exists exp"
msgstr ""
"We check if the name servers of each of your receiving mail servers (MX) provide a TLSA record for DANE. \n"
"\n"
"As DNSSEC is preconditional for DANE, this test will fail in case DNSSEC is missing on the mail server domain(s). \n"
"\n"
"Note that the test ignores TLSA records of the types PKIX-TA(0) or PKIX-EE(1) as these should not be used for receiving mail servers.\n"
"\n"
"Furthermore the test will lead to a fail if there is no DNSSEC proof of 'Denial of Existence' for TLSA records. If a signed TLSA record exists but at the same time there is an insecure `NXDOMAIN` for the same domain (due to faulty signer software), the test will also show a fail. The latter two failure scenario's could lead to non-delivery of emails addressed to you by DANE validating mail senders.\n"
"\n"
"See ['IT Security Guidelines for Transport Layer Security (TLS) v2.1'](https://english.ncsc.nl/publications/publications/2021/january/19/it-security-guidelines-for-transport-layer-security-2.1) from NCSC-NL, Appendix A, under 'Certificate pinning and DANE' (in English)."

msgid "detail mail tls dane-exists label"
msgstr "DANE existence"

msgid "detail mail tls dane-exists tech table"
msgstr "Mail server (MX)|DANE TLSA record existent"

msgid "detail mail tls dane-exists verdict bad"
msgstr ""
"At least one of your mail server domains does *not* provide a TLSA record \n"
"for DANE."

msgid "detail mail tls dane-exists verdict bogus"
msgstr ""
"At least one of your mail server domains does *not* provide DNSSEC proof "
"that DANE TLSA records do not exist. This could lead to non-deliverability "
"of mail sent to you by DANE validating mail senders. You should ask your "
"name server operator to fix this issue."

msgid "detail mail tls dane-exists verdict good"
msgstr "All your mail server domains provide a TLSA record for DANE."

msgid "detail mail tls dane-rollover exp"
msgstr ""
"We check if there is an active scheme with at least two DANE TLSA records to reliably handle certificate rollovers on your receiving mail servers (MX).\n"
"\n"
"Such a scheme will be proven useful when there is a need to update your mail server certificate(s). It can prevent that DANE becomes invalid during the transition period which could endanger mail deliverability at your domain. A rollover scheme could but does not need to be 'active' all the time.\n"
"\n"
"We recommend you to apply one of the following two schemes with double DANE TLSA records:\n"
"\n"
"1. Current + Next (\"3 1 1\" + \"3 1 1\"): Publish two \"DANE-EE(3) SPKI(1) SHA2-256(1)\" records, one for the current and one for the next TLS certificate of your mail server. \n"
"2. Current + Issuer CA (\"3 1 1\" + \"2 1 1\"): Publish a \"DANE-EE(3) SPKI(1) SHA2-256(1)\" record for the current TLS certificate of your mail server, and also a \"DANE-TA(2) SPKI(1) SHA2-256(1)\" record for the current root or intermediate certificate of the (not necessarily public) certificate authority. \n"
"\n"
"The test also accepts other combinations of DANE TLSA records i.e. \"3 x x\"  + \"3 x x\" or \"3 x x\" + \"2 x x\". However other types than the above will generally be more error prone and less interoperable. \n"
"\n"
"*Requirement level: Optional*"

msgid "detail mail tls dane-rollover label"
msgstr "DANE rollover scheme"

msgid "detail mail tls dane-rollover tech table"
msgstr "Mail server (MX)|DANE rollover scheme"

msgid "detail mail tls dane-rollover verdict bad"
msgstr ""
"At least one of your mail server domains does *not* have an active DANE "
"scheme for a reliable rollover of certificate keys."

msgid "detail mail tls dane-rollover verdict good"
msgstr ""
"All your mail server domains have an active DANE scheme for a reliable "
"rollover of certificate keys."

msgid "detail mail tls dane-valid exp"
msgstr ""
"We check if the DANE fingerprints presented by your mail server domains are valid for your mail server certificates. \n"
"\n"
"DANE allows you to publish information about your mail server certificates in a special DNS record, called TLSA record. Sending mail servers can check the authenticity of your certificates not only through the certificate authority but also through the TLSA records. A sending mail server can also use the TLSA record as a signal to only connect via STARTTLS (and not unencrypted). When the DANE fingerprint of a receiving mail server is checked by the sending mail server, an active attacker who is able to manipulate the mail traffic cannot strip STARTTLS encryption. "

msgid "detail mail tls dane-valid label"
msgstr "DANE validity"

msgid "detail mail tls dane-valid tech table"
msgstr "Mail server (MX)|DANE TLSA record valid"

msgid "detail mail tls dane-valid verdict bad"
msgstr ""
"At least one of your mailservers does *not* have any valid DANE "
"fingerprints. Either someone manipulated the response of your mail server, "
"or your mail server has a serious DANE configuration error. The latter makes"
" your domain unreachable for any sending mail server that checks DANE "
"fingerprints. You should contact your mail provider as soon as possible."

msgid "detail mail tls dane-valid verdict good"
msgstr ""
"Each of your mailservers has at least one valid DANE fingerprint. This "
"allows sending mail servers that support DANE verification to set up an "
"authenticated encrypted transport connection with your receiving mail "
"servers."

msgid "detail mail tls fs-params exp"
msgstr ""
"We check if the public parameters used in Diffie-Hellman key exchange by your receiving mail servers (MX) are secure.\n"
"\n"
"**ECDHE**: The security of elliptic curve Diffie-Hellman (ECDHE) ephemeral key exchange depends on the used elliptic curve. We check if the bit-length of the used elliptic curves is a least 224 bits. Currently we are not able to check the elliptic curve name.\n"
"\n"
"**DHE**: The security of Diffie-Hellman Ephemeral (DHE) key exchange depends on the lengths of the public and secret keys used within the chosen finite field group. We test if your DHE public key material uses one of the predefined finite field groups that are specified in [RFC 7919](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc7919). Self-generated groups are 'Insufficient'.\n"
"\n"
"The larger key sizes required for the use of DHE come with a performance penalty. Carefully evaluate and use ECDHE instead of DHE if you can.\n"
"\n"
"**RSA as an alternative**: Besides ECDHE and DHE, RSA can be used for key exchange. However, it is at risk of becoming insufficiently secure (current status 'phase out'). The RSA public parameters are tested in the subtest 'Public key of certificate'. Note that RSA is considered as 'good' for certificate verification.\n"
"\n"
"See ['IT Security Guidelines for Transport Layer Security (TLS) v2.1'](https://english.ncsc.nl/publications/publications/2021/january/19/it-security-guidelines-for-transport-layer-security-2.1) from NCSC-NL, guideline B5-1 and table 9 for ECDHE, and guideline B6-1 and table 10 for DHE (in English).\n"
"\n"
"---\n"
"**Elliptic curve for ECDHE**\n"
"\n"
"* Good: `secp384r1`, `secp256r1`, `x448`, and `x25519`\n"
"* Phase out: `secp224r1`\n"
"* Insufficient: Other curves\n"
"\n"
"**Finite field group for DHE**\n"
"\n"
"* Sufficient:\n"
"\n"
"    * [ffdhe4096](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/internetstandards/dhe_groups/master/ffdhe4096.pem) (RFC 7919)  \n"
"      sha256 checksum: `64852d6890ff9e62eecd1ee89c72af9af244dfef5b853bcedea3dfd7aade22b3`\n"
"    * [ffdhe3072](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/internetstandards/dhe_groups/master/ffdhe3072.pem) (RFC 7919)  \n"
"      sha256 checksum: `c410cc9c4fd85d2c109f7ebe5930ca5304a52927c0ebcb1a11c5cf6b2386bbab`  \n"
"    * Note that we also test for ffdhe8192 and ffdhe6144. However their limited gain in security rarely outweighs the loss in performance.\n"
"\n"
"* Phase out:\n"
"\n"
"    * [ffdhe2048](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/internetstandards/dhe_groups/master/ffdhe2048.pem) (RFC 7919)  \n"
"      sha256 checksum: `9ba6429597aeed2d8617a7705b56e96d044f64b07971659382e426675105654b`\n"
"\n"
"* Insufficient: Other groups\n"
"\n"
"---\n"
"\n"
"Note: the above names are based on the [IANA naming conventions](https://www.iana.org/assignments/tls-parameters/tls-parameters.xhtml). Sometimes alternative names are used to refer to the same curves, like `prime256v1` (ANSI) and `NIST P-256` for `secp256r1`."

msgid "detail mail tls fs-params label"
msgstr "Key exchange parameters"

msgid "detail mail tls fs-params tech table"
msgstr "Mail server (MX)|Affected parameters|Security level"

msgid "detail mail tls fs-params verdict bad"
msgstr ""
"At least one of your mail servers supports *insufficiently* secure "
"parameters for Diffie-Hellman key exchange."

msgid "detail mail tls fs-params verdict good"
msgstr ""
"All your mail servers support secure parameters for Diffie-Hellman key "
"exchange."

msgid "detail mail tls fs-params verdict na"
msgstr ""
"This subtest is not applicable as your mail servers do not support Diffie-"
"Hellman key exchange. Note that RSA is an alternative for key exchange, but "
"has the *phase out* status."

msgid "detail mail tls fs-params verdict phase-out"
msgstr ""
"At least one of your mail servers supports parameters for Diffie-Hellman key"
" exchange that have a *phase out* status, because they are known to be "
"fragile and are at risk of of becoming *insufficiently* secure."

msgid "detail mail tls kex-hash-func exp"
msgstr ""
"We check if your receiving mail servers (MX) support secure hash functions to create the digital signature during key exchange.\n"
"\n"
"A receiving mail server uses a digital signature during the key exchange to prove ownership of the secret key corresponding to the certificate. The mail server creates this digital signature by signing the output of a hash function. \n"
"\n"
"See ['IT Security Guidelines for Transport Layer Security (TLS) v2.1'](https://english.ncsc.nl/publications/publications/2021/january/19/it-security-guidelines-for-transport-layer-security-2.1) from NCSC-NL, table 5.\n"
"\n"
"*Requirement level: Recommended*\n"
"\n"
"---\n"
"**SHA2 support for signatures**\n"
"\n"
"* Good: Yes (SHA-256, SHA-384 or SHA-512 supported)\n"
"* Phase out: No (SHA-256, SHA-384 of SHA-512 *not* supported)"

msgid "detail mail tls kex-hash-func label"
msgstr "Hash function for key exchange"

msgid "detail mail tls kex-hash-func tech table"
msgstr "Mail server (MX)|SHA2 support for signatures"

msgid "detail mail tls kex-hash-func verdict good"
msgstr "All your mail servers support secure hash functions for key exchange."

msgid "detail mail tls kex-hash-func verdict other"
msgstr ""
"We were unable to determine the hash function used by at least one of your "
"mail servers. This could be because the cipher combination used has no "
"signature for certificate verification (e.g it uses RSA key exchange or is "
"anonymous i.e. `anon`)."

msgid "detail mail tls kex-hash-func verdict phase-out"
msgstr ""
"At least one of your mail servers does *not* support a secure hash function "
"for key exchange. You should *phase out* this setting deliberately, because "
"it is at risk of becoming *insufficiently* secure in the future."

msgid "detail mail tls ocsp-stapling exp"
msgstr ""
"OUTDATED TEXT; TEST NOT USED   \n"
"We check if your receiving mail server supports the [TLS Certificate Status extension](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc6961) \n"
"aka OCSP stapling. With OCSP stapling your mail server can provide OCSP \n"
"responses itself which removes the need for the TLS client to verify the \n"
"validity of the mail server certificate directly with the certificate \n"
"supplier, and thus avoids exposing potentially privacy sensitive data about \n"
"the client to the certificate supplier. It also does not require \n"
"connectivity between client and certificate supplier and is faster. See \n"
"['IT Security Guidelines for Transport Layer Security (TLS)'](https://www.ncsc.nl/english/current-topics/factsheets/it-security-guidelines-for-transport-layer-security-tls.html), guideline B9-1 (in English).\n"
"\n"
"When connecting to your mail server we use the TLS Certificate Status \n"
"extension to request OCSP data be included in the server response. If your \n"
"mail server includes OCSP data in the response we then verify that the OCSP \n"
"data is signed by a known certificate authority."

msgid "detail mail tls ocsp-stapling label"
msgstr ""
"OUTDATED TEXT; TEST NOT USED   \n"
"OCSP stapling"

msgid "detail mail tls ocsp-stapling tech table"
msgstr ""
"OUTDATED TEXT; TEST NOT USED  \n"
"Mail server (MX)|OCSP stapling"

msgid "detail mail tls ocsp-stapling verdict bad"
msgstr ""
"OUTDATED TEXT; TEST NOT USED  \n"
"At least one of your mail servers supports OCSP stapling but responds with invalid data"

msgid "detail mail tls ocsp-stapling verdict good"
msgstr ""
"OUTDATED TEXT; TEST NOT USED  \n"
"Your mail servers support OCSP stapling."

msgid "detail mail tls ocsp-stapling verdict ok"
msgstr ""
"OUTDATED TEXT; TEST NOT USED  \n"
"At least one of your mail servers does not support OCSP stapling."

msgid "detail mail tls renegotiation-client exp"
msgstr ""
"We check if a sending mail server can initiate a renegotiation with your receiving mail servers (MX). \n"
"\n"
"Allowing sending mail servers to initiate renegotiation is generally not necessary and opens a receiving mail server to DoS attacks inside a TLS connection. An attacker can perform similar DoS-attacks without client-initiated renegotiation by opening many parallel TLS connections, but these are easier to detect and defend against using standard mitigations. Note that client-initiated renegotiation impacts availability and not confidentiality. \n"
"\n"
"See ['IT Security Guidelines for Transport Layer Security (TLS) v2.1'](https://english.ncsc.nl/publications/publications/2021/january/19/it-security-guidelines-for-transport-layer-security-2.1) from NCSC-NL, guideline B8-1 and table 13 (in English).\n"
"\n"
"*Requirement level: Optional*\n"
"\n"
"---\n"
"\n"
"**Client-initiated renegotiation**\n"
"\n"
"* Good: Off (or N/A for TLS 1.3)\n"
"* Sufficient: On"

msgid "detail mail tls renegotiation-client label"
msgstr "Client-initiated renegotiation"

msgid "detail mail tls renegotiation-client tech table"
msgstr "Mail server (MX)|Client-initiated renegotiation"

msgid "detail mail tls renegotiation-client verdict bad"
msgstr ""
"At least one of your mail servers allows for client-initiated renegotiation,"
" which could have negative impact on the availability of your mail server."

msgid "detail mail tls renegotiation-client verdict good"
msgstr ""
"All your mail servers do not allow for client-initiated renegotiation."

msgid "detail mail tls renegotiation-secure exp"
msgstr ""
"We check if your mail servers (MX) support secure renegotiation. \n"
"\n"
"Older versions of TLS (prior to TLS 1.3) allow forcing a new handshake. This so-called renegotiation was insecure in its original design. The standard was repaired and a safer renegotiation mechanism was added. The old version is since called insecure renegotiation and should be disabled.\n"
"\n"
"See ['IT Security Guidelines for Transport Layer Security (TLS) v2.1'](https://english.ncsc.nl/publications/publications/2021/january/19/it-security-guidelines-for-transport-layer-security-2.1) from NCSC-NL, guideline B8-1 and table 12 (in English).\n"
"\n"
"---\n"
"**Insecure renegotiation**\n"
"\n"
"* Good: Off (or N/A for TLS 1.3)\n"
"* Insufficient: On"

msgid "detail mail tls renegotiation-secure label"
msgstr "Secure renegotiation"

msgid "detail mail tls renegotiation-secure tech table"
msgstr "Mail server (MX)|Secure renegotiation"

msgid "detail mail tls renegotiation-secure verdict bad"
msgstr ""
"At least one of your mail servers supports insecure renegotiation, which is obviously *not* \n"
"secure."

msgid "detail mail tls renegotiation-secure verdict good"
msgstr "All your mail servers support secure renegotiation."

msgid "detail mail tls starttls-exists exp"
msgstr ""
"We check if your receiving mail servers (MX) support STARTTLS. If so, we also check in the subtests of this test category whether STARTTLS is configured sufficiently secure. \n"
"\n"
"Because of performance reasons at most ten mail servers over either IPv6 or IPv4 are tested for STARTTLS and DANE.\n"
"\n"
"Note that the email test does not fall back to A/AAAA records for mail servers in case of absence of an MX record.\n"
"\n"
"*Non-receiving domain*:\n"
"\n"
"1. Null MX: In case you do not want to receive mail on your domain that has A/AAAA records, we advise you to use \"Null MX\" ([RFC 7505](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc7505)). Note that a \"Null MX record\" should not be combined with a normal MX record that is pointing to a mail host.\n"
"2. No MX: In case your domain does not have A/AAAA records and you do not want to receive mail on it, we advise you to configure no MX record at all (i.e. even *not* an \"Null MX\" record).\n"
"\n"
"* If we detect any of the above two cases, the subtests in the STARTTLS and DANE category are not applicable. This also goes for the mail server specific subtests in the categories for IPv6 and DNSSEC. Other subtests of the email test (e.g. for DMARC) are still applicable. \n"
"* Note that having a \"Null MX\" record or no MX record could also impact sending mail, because receiving servers may reject email that has an invalid return address.\n"
"\n"
"For a \"good practice on domains without mail\" see the [explanation of the \"DMARC policy\" subtest](#control-panel-9)."

msgid "detail mail tls starttls-exists label"
msgstr "STARTTLS available"

msgid "detail mail tls starttls-exists tech table"
msgstr "Mail server (MX)|STARTTLS"

msgid "detail mail tls starttls-exists verdict bad"
msgstr "At least one of your mail servers does *not* offer STARTTLS."

msgid "detail mail tls starttls-exists verdict good"
msgstr "All your mail servers offer STARTTLS."

msgid "detail mail tls starttls-exists verdict invalid-null-mx"
msgstr ""
"Your domain advertises a \"Null MX\" record indicating that it does not "
"accept email. However, either your domain does not have A/AAAA records, "
"making the \"Null MX\" record unnecessary. Or on your domain a receiving "
"mail server is set by another MX record, making the \"Null MX\" conflicting."

msgid "detail mail tls starttls-exists verdict no-null-mx"
msgstr ""
"No receiving mail servers (MX) are set on your domain that has A/AAAA "
"records. We recommend you to explicitly indicate that your domain does not "
"accept email by configuring a \"Null MX\" record. Do not use a \"Null MX\" "
"record and set an MX if you do want to send email from this domain name, as "
"receiving servers may reject email that has an invalid return address."

msgid "detail mail tls starttls-exists verdict null-mx"
msgstr ""
"Your domain name that has A/AAAA records clearly indicates with a \"Null "
"MX\" record that it does not accept e-mail. This is fine if you do not want "
"to receive email. Do not use a \"Null MX\" record and set an MX if you do "
"want to send email from this domain name, as receiving servers may reject "
"email that has an invalid return address."

msgid "detail mail tls starttls-exists verdict null-mx-with-other-mx"
msgstr ""
"Your domain advertises a \"Null MX\" record indicating that it does not "
"accept email. However, on your domain a receiving mail server is set by "
"another MX record, making the \"Null MX\" conflicting."

msgid "detail mail tls starttls-exists verdict null-mx-without-a-aaaa"
msgstr ""
"Your domain advertises a \"Null MX\" record indicating that it does not "
"accept email. However, your domain does not have A/AAAA records, making the "
"\"Null MX\" record unnecessary."

msgid "detail mail tls starttls-exists verdict other"
msgstr "At least one of your mail servers is unreachable."

msgid "detail mail tls starttls-exists verdict other-2"
msgstr ""
"No receiving mail servers (MX) are set on your domain that does not have "
"A/AAAA records. This is fine if you do not want to receive email. "

msgid "detail mail tls version exp"
msgstr ""
"We check if your mail servers (MX) support secure TLS versions only. \n"
"\n"
"A mail server may support more than one TLS version. \n"
"\n"
"Note that quite some mail servers only support older TLS versions. If the sending and receiving mail server both do not support the same TLS version, they will usually fall back to unencrypted mail transport. Because of that it could be advisable to keep supporting TLS versions with a 'phase out' status for a while. Make an informed decision based on log data on when to disable these 'phase out' TLS versions.\n"
"\n"
"See ['IT Security Guidelines for Transport Layer Security (TLS) v2.1'](https://english.ncsc.nl/publications/publications/2021/january/19/it-security-guidelines-for-transport-layer-security-2.1) from NCSC-NL, guideline B1-1 and table 1 (in English).\n"
"\n"
"---\n"
"**Version**\n"
"\n"
"* Good: TLS 1.3 \n"
"* Sufficient: TLS 1.2\n"
"* Phase out: TLS 1.1 and 1.0\n"
"* Insufficient: SSL 3.0, 2.0 and 1.0"

